     multiValues.put(&quot;array2&quot;, array2);

     return multiValue;

    }

Then in the calling function you can get these two values from the `Map` `multiValues` by using the keys -   &quot;array1&quot;, &quot;array2&quot;:

    String[] array1 = (String[]) multiValues.get(&quot;array1&quot;);
    int[] array2 = (int[]) multiValues.get(&quot;array2&quot;);

You didn&#39;t include the source for WebClient, but this, `WebClient.create(`, hints that you&#39;re creating an instance of WebClient.  If you want this to be a mock, then you need to assign that to `Mockito.mock(WebClient.class)`

Such as this

    WebClient webClient = Mockito.mock(WebClient.class);

You also need to define behavior on your mock, or this will throw a NPE when it reaches the `.uri()` method call because the return value isn&#39;t defined on your mock.  So you&#39;ll have to configure your mock to return properly for all those chained methods.  If that&#39;s the Spring WebClient, I believe those return a Builder so you&#39;ll need one of these mocked out as well.

